  "source": "Psichiatry_DSM-5_textbook_data.txt - Major Depressive Disorder (MDD) is characterized by one or more Major Depressive Episodes, defined as at least 2 weeks of depressed mood or loss of interest or pleasure in nearly all activities, accompanied by at least four additional symptoms such as changes in sleep, appetite or weight, energy, concentration, and psychomotor activity; feelings of worthlessness or guilt; and recurrent thoughts of death or suicidal ideation. These symptoms must cause clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other important areas of functioning, and must not be attributable to the physiological effects of a substance or another medical condition. The diagnosis requires careful exclusion of Bipolar Disorder, as treatment approaches differ significantly. MDD occurs twice as commonly in women than men, with a lifetime prevalence of approximately 20% in women and 10% in men. Risk factors include family history (indicating genetic vulnerability), childhood adversity, recent stressful life events, and certain personality traits such as neuroticism. The typical age of onset is in the 20s, but MDD can begin at any age, even in childhood. MDD is considered a highly recurrent disorder, with at least 50% of individuals who recover from a first episode experiencing one or more additional episodes during their lifetime. With each successive episode, the probability of further recurrence increases. Physical symptoms are common in MDD and include pain complaints, fatigue, appetite changes, and sleep disturbances, particularly early morning awakening (terminal insomnia). Cognitive symptoms such as indecisiveness, rumination, and poor concentration are also frequent and contribute significantly to functional impairment. Diagnostic evaluation typically includes screening tools such as the Patient Health Questionnaire-9 (PHQ-9), which quantifies symptom severity, and laboratory tests to rule out medical conditions that might mimic depression, including thyroid dysfunction, anemia, vitamin deficiencies, and metabolic disorders. Treatment options include psychotherapy (particularly cognitive-behavioral therapy and interpersonal therapy), antidepressant medications (selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors being first-line agents for most patients), or a combination of both. For severe cases or those with psychotic features, electroconvulsive therapy may be considered. Prognosis is generally favorable with appropriate treatment, though many individuals experience some degree of residual symptoms between episodes, and a minority develop a chronic course with limited periods of remission.",
  "category": "Psychiatry"
